As Nigerian children continue to suffer and die from avoidable illnesses and the country’s disease index remains high, the call for Nigerian government to redouble its effort towards improved immunisation in the country has been renewed. According to the Nigeria Demographic and Health Survey (NDHS-2018), only 31 per cent of children age 12-23 months have received all eight basic vaccinations which is, one dose each of BCG and measles vaccine and three doses each of DPT-HepB-Hib and polio vaccine. The survey, which was analysed by a Monitoring and Evaluation Specialist, Maureen Zubie-Okolo, at the two-day Media Dialogue on the NDHS, SDGs, Data and  Solution Journalism, organised by UNICEF in collaboration with the Child Rights Information Bureau, Federal Ministry of Information, recently in Port Harcourt, Rivers State, highlighted immunisation coverage as one of the indicators used to monitor progress toward reductions in child morbidity and mortality, as it is one of the most cost-effective public health interventions. According to the report, “All basic vaccinations for children age 12-23 months include: One dose of BCG vaccine, which protects against tuberculosis, three doses of DPT-containing vaccine, which protects against diphtheria, pertussis (whooping cough), and tetanus, three doses of oral polio vaccine (excluding polio vaccine given at birth) one dose of measles vaccine. It however showed that vaccination coverage in the country has improved over the past 10 years, explaining that the percentage of children age 12-23 months who received all basic vaccinations increased from 23 per cent in 2008 to 31per cent  in 2018 while the percentage of children who received none of the basic vaccinations declined from 29 per cent  to 19per cent  during the same period. “However, while these trends show improvement, they still fall short of the Sustainable Development Goal 3, for which the target is achieving more than 90 per cent coverage of all basic vaccinations among children age 12-23 months,” the report noted. 